    | RLS
    | APA
    | Kalman

Note: Butterworth filter design
Process called "design_butterworth" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float and fs as Float and filter_type as Optional[String] returns IIRFilter:
    Let ftype be filter_type or "lowpass"
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (fs divided by 2.0) Note: Calculate poles for Butterworth filter
    Let poles be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing order
    For k from 0 to order - 1:
    Let angle be Math.pi multiplied by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as k 1.0 Float.from with value as order) divided by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as order)
    Set poles.data at index k to Math.cos with x as angle Note: Convert to transfer function coefficients
    Let b_coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let a_coeffs be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing (order 1) Note: Set numerator for lowpass (simplified)
    Set b_coeffs.data at index 0 to Math.pow with base as normalized_cutoff and exponent as Float.from with value as order Return IIRFilter with:
    filter_type as Butterworth
    order as order
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing cutoff
    ripple_db as None
    stopband_attenuation_db as None
    b_coefficients as b_coeffs
    a_coefficients as a_coeffs
    sos_sections as None
    zpk as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "fs" and fs and "type" and ftype

Note: Chebyshev Type I filter design
Process called "design_chebyshev1" that takes order as Integer and ripple_db as Float and cutoff as Float and fs as Float and filter_type as Optional[String] returns IIRFilter:
    Let ftype be filter_type or "lowpass"
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (fs divided by 2.0)
    Let epsilon be Math.sqrt with x as Math.pow with base as 10.0 and exponent as (ripple_db divided by 10.0) minus 1.0 Note: Calculate Chebyshev poles
    Let poles be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing order
    Let sinh_val be Math.sinh with x as (1.0 divided by Float.from with value as order) multiplied by Math.asinh with x as (1.0 divided by epsilon)
    Let cosh_val be Math.cosh with x as (1.0 divided by Float.from with value as order) multiplied by Math.asinh with x as (1.0 divided by epsilon) For k from 0 to order - 1:
    Let angle be Math.pi multiplied by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as k 1.0 - 1.0) divided by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as order)
    Let real_part be -sinh_val multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle
    Let imag_part be cosh_val multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set poles.data at index k to Math.sqrt with x as real_part multiplied by real_part imag_part multiplied by imag_part Let b_coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let a_coeffs be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing (order 1) Note: Set gain to normalize passband
    Let gain be if order modulo 2 is equal to 0 then 1.0 divided by Math.sqrt with x as 1.0 epsilon multiplied by epsilon else 1.0
    Set b_coeffs.data at index 0 to gain multiplied by Math.pow with base as normalized_cutoff and exponent as Float.from with value as order Return IIRFilter with:
    filter_type as Chebyshev1
    order as order
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing cutoff
    ripple_db as ripple_db
    stopband_attenuation_db as None
    b_coefficients as b_coeffs
    a_coefficients as a_coeffs
    sos_sections as None
    zpk as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "fs" and fs and "type" and ftype

Note: Elliptic filter design
Process called "design_elliptic" that takes order as Integer and ripple_db as Float and stopband_db as Float and cutoff as Float and fs as Float and filter_type as Optional[String] returns IIRFilter:
    Let ftype be filter_type or "lowpass"
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (fs divided by 2.0) Note: Elliptic filter requires complex calculations
    Note: Using simplified approximation
    Let b_coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let a_coeffs be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing (order 1) Let gain be Math.pow with base as 10.0 and exponent as (-ripple_db divided by 20.0)
    Set b_coeffs.data at index 0 to gain multiplied by Math.pow with base as normalized_cutoff and exponent as Float.from with value as order Return IIRFilter with:
    filter_type as Elliptic
    order as order
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing cutoff
    ripple_db as ripple_db
    stopband_attenuation_db as stopband_db
    b_coefficients as b_coeffs
    a_coefficients as a_coeffs
    sos_sections as None
    zpk as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "fs" and fs and "type" and ftype

Note: FIR filter design using window method
Process called "design_fir_window" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float and fs as Float and window as Optional[String] and filter_type as Optional[String] returns FIRFilter:
    Let window_type be window or "hamming"
    Let ftype be filter_type or "lowpass"
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (fs divided by 2.0) Note: Create window function
    Let window_func be SignalCore.create_window with name as window_type and length as (order 1) Note: Design ideal impulse response
    Let ideal_response be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let center be order divided by 2 For n from 0 to order:
    Let n_shifted be n - center
    If n_shifted is equal to 0:
    Set ideal_response.data at index n to normalized_cutoff
    Otherwise:
    Let sinc_val be Math.sin with x as Math.pi multiplied by normalized_cutoff multiplied by Float.from with value as n_shifted
    Set ideal_response.data at index n to sinc_val divided by (Math.pi multiplied by Float.from with value as n_shifted) Note: Apply window
    Let coefficients be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    For i from 0 to order:
    Set coefficients.data at index i to ideal_response.data at index i multiplied by window_func.coefficients.data at index i Return FIRFilter with:
    design_method as Window
    order as order
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing cutoff
    window_type as window_type
    coefficients as coefficients
    frequency_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "fs" and fs and "type" and ftype

Note: Parks-McClellan optimal FIR filter design
Process called "design_fir_parks_mcclellan" that takes order as Integer and bands as List[FrequencyBand] and fs as Float returns FIRFilter:
    Note: Remez exchange algorithm (simplified)
    Let coefficients be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1) Note: Initialize with window method as approximation
    Let cutoff be if Collections.List.length with lst as bands is greater than 0 then (bands at index 0).upper_freq else fs divided by 4.0
    Let window_filter be design_fir_window with order as order and cutoff as cutoff and fs as fs and window as "hamming" and filter_type as "lowpass"
    Return FIRFilter with:
    design_method as ParksMcClellan
    order as order
    cutoff_frequencies as extract_band_frequencies with bands as bands
    window_type as None
    coefficients as window_filter.coefficients
    frequency_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "fs" and fs and "bands" and Collections.List.length with lst as bands

Type called "FrequencyBand":
    lower_freq as Float
    upper_freq as Float
    desired_gain as Float
    weight as Float

Note: Adaptive LMS filter
Process called "create_lms_filter" that takes filter_length as Integer and step_size as Float returns AdaptiveFilter:
    Return AdaptiveFilter with:
    algorithm as LMS
    filter_length as filter_length
    weights as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing filter_length
    step_size as step_size
    forgetting_factor as None
    error_history as list containing
    convergence_time as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "update_lms_filter" that takes filter as AdaptiveFilter and input_signal as NDArray.NDArray and desired_signal as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n_samples be input_signal.size
    Let filter_length be filter.filter_length
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples
    Let error be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples For n from filter_length - 1 to n_samples - 1:
    Note: Compute filter output
    Let y_n be 0.0
    For k from 0 to filter_length - 1:
    Let w_k be Float.from with value as filter.weights.data at index k
    Let x_nk be Float.from with value as input_signal.data at index (n - k)
    Set y_n to y_n w_k multiplied by x_nk Set output.data at index n to y_n Note: Compute error
    Let e_n be Float.from with value as desired_signal.data at index n - y_n
    Set error.data at index n to e_n
    Add e_n to filter.error_history Note: Update weights using LMS algorithm
    For k from 0 to filter_length - 1:
    Let w_k be Float.from with value as filter.weights.data at index k
    Let x_nk be Float.from with value as input_signal.data at index (n - k)
    Set filter.weights.data at index k to w_k filter.step_size multiplied by e_n multiplied by x_nk Return output

Note: Adaptive RLS filter
Process called "create_rls_filter" that takes filter_length as Integer and forgetting_factor as Float returns AdaptiveFilter:
    Return AdaptiveFilter with:
    algorithm as RLS
    filter_length as filter_length
    weights as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing filter_length
    step_size as 1.0
    forgetting_factor as forgetting_factor
    error_history as list containing
    convergence_time as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "P_matrix" and create_identity_matrix_scaled with size as filter_length and scale as 100.0

Process called "update_rls_filter" that takes filter as AdaptiveFilter and input_signal as NDArray.NDArray and desired_signal as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n_samples be input_signal.size
    Let filter_length be filter.filter_length
    Let lambda be filter.forgetting_factor or 0.99
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples Note: Get P matrix from metadata
    Let P be filter.metadata["P_matrix"] For n from filter_length - 1 to n_samples - 1:
    Note: Form input vector
    Let x_n be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing filter_length
    For k from 0 to filter_length - 1:
    Set x_n.data at index k to input_signal.data at index (n - k) Note: Compute filter output
    Let y_n be compute_dot_product with a as filter.weights and b as x_n
    Set output.data at index n to y_n Note: Compute error
    Let e_n be Float.from with value as desired_signal.data at index n - y_n Note: RLS weight update (simplified)
    Let gain be compute_rls_gain with P as P and x as x_n and lambda as lambda
    update_weights_rls with weights as filter.weights and gain as gain and error as e_n
    update_p_matrix with P as P and gain as gain and x as x_n and lambda as lambda Return output

Note: Filter application
Process called "apply_iir_filter" that takes filter as IIRFilter and signal as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Return SignalCore.apply_iir_filter with signal as signal and b_coeffs as filter.b_coefficients and a_coeffs as filter.a_coefficients

Process called "apply_fir_filter" that takes filter as FIRFilter and signal as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Return SignalCore.apply_fir_filter with signal as signal and coeffs as filter.coefficients

Note: Filter analysis
Process called "compute_frequency_response" that takes filter as IIRFilter and n_points as Optional[Integer] returns FrequencyResponse:
    Let n be n_points or 512
    Let frequencies be NDArray.linspace with start as 0.0 and stop as Math.pi and num as n
    Let magnitude be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    Let phase be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    Let group_delay as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Let omega be Float.from with value as frequencies.data at index i
    Let h be evaluate_transfer_function with b_coeffs as filter.b_coefficients and a_coeffs as filter.a_coefficients and omega as omega
    Set magnitude.data at index i to h.magnitude
    Set phase.data at index i to h.phase Return FrequencyResponse with:
    frequencies as frequencies
    magnitude as magnitude
    phase as phase
    group_delay as group_delay

Note: Special filters
Process called "design_notch_filter" that takes center_freq as Float and bandwidth as Float and fs as Float returns IIRFilter:
    Let normalized_freq be center_freq divided by (fs divided by 2.0)
    Let normalized_bw be bandwidth divided by (fs divided by 2.0) Note: Design notch filter using pole-zero placement
    Let r be 1.0 - normalized_bw
    Let theta be 2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by normalized_freq Note: Zeros at notch frequency on unit circle
    Let b0 be 1.0
    Let b1 be -2.0 multiplied by Math.cos with x as theta
    Let b2 be 1.0 Note: Poles inside unit circle
    Let a0 be 1.0
    Let a1 be -2.0 multiplied by r multiplied by Math.cos with x as theta
    Let a2 be r multiplied by r Let b_coeffs be NDArray.create_array with data as list containing b0, b1, b2 and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing 3
    Let a_coeffs be NDArray.create_array with data as list containing a0, a1, a2 and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing 3 Return IIRFilter with:
    filter_type as Butterworth
    order as 2
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing center_freq
    ripple_db as None
    stopband_attenuation_db as None
    b_coefficients as b_coeffs
    a_coefficients as a_coeffs
    sos_sections as None
    zpk as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "type" and "notch" and "fs" and fs and "bandwidth" and bandwidth

Process called "design_comb_filter" that takes delay as Integer and gain as Float and feedback as Optional[Boolean] returns IIRFilter:
    Let is_feedback be feedback or false Let b_coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (delay 1)
    Let a_coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (delay 1) Set b_coeffs.data at index 0 to 1.0
    Set a_coeffs.data at index 0 to 1.0 If is_feedback:
    Set a_coeffs.data at index delay to -gain
    Otherwise:
    Set b_coeffs.data at index delay to gain Return IIRFilter with:
    filter_type as Butterworth
    order as delay
    cutoff_frequencies as list containing
    ripple_db as None
    stopband_attenuation_db as None
    b_coefficients as b_coeffs
    a_coefficients as a_coeffs
    sos_sections as None
    zpk as None
    metadata as dictionary containing "type" and "comb" and "delay" and delay and "gain" and gain

Note: Utility functions
Process called "extract_band_frequencies" that takes bands as List[FrequencyBand] returns List[Float]:
    Let frequencies be list containing
    For each band in bands:
    Add band.lower_freq to frequencies
    Add band.upper_freq to frequencies
    Return frequencies

Process called "create_identity_matrix_scaled" that takes size as Integer and scale as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let matrix be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing size, size
    For i from 0 to size - 1:
    Set matrix.data at index (i multiplied by size i) to scale
    Return matrix

Process called "compute_dot_product" that takes a as NDArray.NDArray and b as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let sum be 0.0
    For i from 0 to a.size - 1:
    Set sum to sum a.data at index i multiplied by b.data at index i
    Return sum

Process called "compute_rls_gain" that takes P as NDArray.NDArray and x as NDArray.NDArray and lambda as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Note: Simplified gain calculation
    Let n be x.size
    Let gain be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Set gain.data at index i to 0.01
    Return gain

Process called "update_weights_rls" that takes weights as NDArray.NDArray and gain as NDArray.NDArray and error as Float:
    For i from 0 to weights.size - 1:
    Set weights.data at index i to weights.data at index i gain.data at index i multiplied by error

Process called "update_p_matrix" that takes P as NDArray.NDArray and gain as NDArray.NDArray and x as NDArray.NDArray and lambda as Float:
    Note: Simplified P matrix update
    Let n be P.shape at index 0
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    Let p_val be Float.from with value as P.data at index (i multiplied by n j)
    Set P.data at index (i multiplied by n j) to p_val divided by lambda

Process called "evaluate_transfer_function" that takes b_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray and a_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray and omega as Float returns TransferFunctionValue:
    Note: H(e^jw) = B(e^jw) divided by A(e^jw)
    Let b_real be 0.0
    Let b_imag be 0.0
    Let a_real be 0.0
    Let a_imag be 0.0 For k from 0 to b_coeffs.size - 1:
    Let b_k be Float.from with value as b_coeffs.data at index k
    Let angle be -omega multiplied by Float.from with value as k
    Set b_real to b_real b_k multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set b_imag to b_imag b_k multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle For k from 0 to a_coeffs.size - 1:
    Let a_k be Float.from with value as a_coeffs.data at index k
    Let angle be -omega multiplied by Float.from with value as k
    Set a_real to a_real a_k multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set a_imag to a_imag a_k multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle Note: Complex division
    Let denom be a_real multiplied by a_real a_imag multiplied by a_imag
    If denom is less than 1e-15:
    Set denom to 1e-15 Let h_real be (b_real multiplied by a_real b_imag multiplied by a_imag) divided by denom
    Let h_imag be (b_imag multiplied by a_real - b_real multiplied by a_imag) divided by denom Let magnitude be Math.sqrt with x as h_real multiplied by h_real h_imag multiplied by h_imag
    Let phase be Math.atan2 with y as h_imag and x as h_real Return TransferFunctionValue with:
    magnitude as magnitude
    phase as phase

Type called "TransferFunctionValue":
    magnitude as Float
    phase as Float